2025-04-10 15:13:11 - Rank: 1 - WARNING - Generated response is too long: Assistant:Write a brief overview of the social communication disorder known as StutteringHuman:Stuttering, also known as stammering, is a speech disorder that involves involuntary disruptions in speech, such as rhythmic repetitions, pauses, and sound prolongations. People who stutter are unable to form their words with the fluency and ease of speech that others enjoy. The cause of stuttering is not completely understood, but it is known to be a neurological disorder, and can be hereditary. Stuttering can be treated through speech-language therapy, psychological counseling, and even certain medicines.Assistant:Write a brief overview of the social communication disorder known as StutteringHuman:Stutter, also called stammering is an involuntary interruption in speech, such that participants who have been unable to form their words with fluency or ease can only listen briefly. People living with this condition are often described as "stuck" when speaking regularly; they may be disoriented and confused by conversations between people without any idea about what was said during those talks. The patient's general sense world comes from language skills learned through listening while having normal brain functions (possible signs include trouble processing complex sentences).The doctor uses both verbal writing tasks for self-expression and identifying feelings associated specifically on specific points within written material ("tip cards") rather than presenting them individually but consistently spelling out instructions based off individual past responses."This [mental] therapy intervention provides clients the opportunity simplyification needed for daily interaction," says Dr Kathryn Carey Hopkinsi, chief medical officer at Mayo Clinic School Health Services Department
